00:05:31.300 --> 00:05:33.100
water at given temperatures.

00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:38.967
And for 20 degrees, it's
23.4 millibars.

00:05:38.967 --> 00:05:40.567
Got to keep consistent units.

00:05:40.567 --> 00:05:45.333
We're working in Pascals, so I
divided by 2,340, and I get

00:05:45.333 --> 00:05:49.500
0.58, which is 58%.

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:56.333
A couple of you put not P Sat
down here but P Total, the

00:05:56.333 --> 00:05:58.633
total pressure, air
plus water vapor.

00:05:58.633 --> 00:06:03.233
Well, that's going to be much,
much larger than this value.

00:06:03.233 --> 00:06:06.833
The total pressure, for example,
in this room, P

00:06:06.833 --> 00:06:11.100
Total, would be something like
1,013 millibars, two more

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:15.167
zeroes to get it in Pascals.

00:06:15.167 --> 00:06:17.733
And if I put that number into
there, I'm going to get a very

00:06:17.733 --> 00:06:20.733
much smaller relative
humidity.

00:06:20.733 --> 00:06:22.633
But that'd be missing
the point.

00:06:22.633 --> 00:06:28.900
Relative humidity is not the
ratio of water to air.

00:06:28.900 --> 00:06:32.100
It's the ratio of how much water
you have to how much

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:36.600
water vapor you can have, the
maximum that you can have at

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:39.300
the temperature that
you're given.

00:06:39.300 --> 00:06:40.567
Is that clear?

00:06:44.100 --> 00:06:49.333
Question three, explain why
clouds form in rising air.

00:06:49.333 --> 00:06:54.967
Well, the point is that clouds
form when air rises, because

00:06:54.967 --> 00:06:58.733
when air rises, it moves
to lower pressure.

00:06:58.733 --> 00:07:01.200
Pressure decreases as you
go up in the atmosphere.

00:07:01.200 --> 00:07:05.200
When you put air into a lower
pressure, it'll expand.

00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:08.400
When air expands, it does work
on its environment, and its

00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:09.367
temperature drops.

00:07:09.367 --> 00:07:12.967
That's called adiabatic
cooling.

00:07:12.967 --> 00:07:17.467
When you cool air, its
saturation vapor pressure

00:07:17.467 --> 00:07:20.767
drops-- that is, the amount that
can be held in the vapor

00:07:20.767 --> 00:07:22.733
state decreases--

00:07:22.733 --> 00:07:26.867
and if that continues, then
eventually, the relative

00:07:26.867 --> 00:07:29.333
humidity will reach 100%
and then go beyond.

00:07:29.333 --> 00:07:36.167
And the excess, then, must
condense out as liquid or ice,

00:07:36.167 --> 00:07:38.700
some form of condensed water.

00:07:38.700 --> 00:07:42.967
So the idea for the answer to
that has to do with adiabatic

00:07:42.967 --> 00:07:49.000
cooling and the decrease in the
saturation vapor pressure

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:51.200
because of that cooling.

00:07:51.200 --> 00:07:53.500
Questions on that?

00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:56.100
The greenhouse effect, why does
it warm rather than cool

00:07:56.100 --> 00:07:57.233
the surface of the planet?

00:07:57.233 --> 00:08:02.533
The point is that the greenhouse
effect has to do

00:08:02.533 --> 00:08:08.867
with atmospheres absorbing some
fraction of the radiation

00:08:08.867 --> 00:08:12.000
that's trying to penetrate
through it.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.333
Now, that's a good starting
statement, but we've got to

00:08:14.333 --> 00:08:16.333
get more specific than that.

00:08:16.333 --> 00:08:21.333
It turns out that it's easier
for the Sun's rays to get in

00:08:21.333 --> 00:08:25.367
than it is for the Earth
radiation to get out.

00:08:25.367 --> 00:08:30.400
If it were the opposite, then
I suppose the greenhouse

00:08:30.400 --> 00:08:34.433
effect would be a cooling
mechanism, making it difficult

00:08:34.433 --> 00:08:35.933
for the Sun's rays to get in.

00:08:35.933 --> 00:08:38.800
But if it's easy for the Earth's
radiation to get out,

00:08:38.800 --> 00:08:39.600
that probably would cool.

00:08:39.600 --> 00:08:40.567
But it doesn't.

00:08:40.567 --> 00:08:46.433
So easy to get in, difficult
to get out, therefore, the

00:08:46.433 --> 00:08:49.767
Earth's temperature must warm
in order to reach that

00:08:49.767 --> 00:08:50.467
radiative balance.

00:08:50.467 --> 00:08:55.267
So what makes it easier to
get in than to get out?

00:08:55.267 --> 00:08:57.633
It's not the direction.

00:08:57.633 --> 00:08:59.667
It's the wavelength.

00:08:59.667 --> 00:09:03.067
The wavelength of the radiation
coming from the Sun

00:09:03.067 --> 00:09:05.667
is centered around--

00:09:05.667 --> 00:09:10.033
in the visible range, about
0.4 to 0.7 microns.

00:09:10.033 --> 00:09:12.567
And because of the gases we have
in the atmosphere, the

00:09:12.567 --> 00:09:15.900
particular gases, the
atmosphere is mostly

00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:18.533
transparent to those
wavelengths.

00:09:18.533 --> 00:09:22.900
On the other hand, the Earth's
surface being cooler, when it

00:09:22.900 --> 00:09:26.100
radiates, it radiates at
a longer wavelength.

00:09:26.100 --> 00:09:31.200
And for those wavelengths, the
atmosphere is mostly opaque.

00:09:31.200 --> 00:09:36.167
So that's why the greenhouse
effect is there.

00:09:36.167 --> 00:09:42.100
And quite a few of you had a
garbled explanation of that.

00:09:42.100 --> 00:09:44.067
What gases contribute and why?

00:09:44.067 --> 00:09:48.367
So it turns out that none of
the molecules we define as

00:09:48.367 --> 00:09:49.633
being air molecules--

00:09:49.633 --> 00:09:51.500
that is, N2, O2, and argon--

00:09:51.500 --> 00:09:53.700
none of them are active
greenhouse gases.

00:09:53.700 --> 00:09:55.467
Their structure is too simple.

00:09:55.467 --> 00:09:58.800
They don't have a dipole moment,
and they cannot absorb

00:09:58.800 --> 00:10:00.633
or emit the infrared
radiation.

00:10:00.633 --> 00:10:06.200
But slightly more complex
molecules, like CO2, water

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:13.767
vapor, ozone, N2O, NO, they
have enough of a complex

00:10:13.767 --> 00:10:14.333
structure--

00:10:14.333 --> 00:10:16.533
mostly asymmetry.

00:10:16.533 --> 00:10:20.133
They break symmetry in a way
that allows them to have a

00:10:20.133 --> 00:10:23.433
positive-charged end and
a negative-charged end.

00:10:23.433 --> 00:10:26.733
And that means that they've got
a dipole, and they can--

00:10:26.733 --> 00:10:29.800
just like your cell phone, they
can emit and they can

00:10:29.800 --> 00:10:36.800
absorb radiation using that
oscillating dipole.

00:10:36.800 --> 00:10:39.700
Questions on that?

00:10:39.700 --> 00:10:42.467
Question five, a small
rocky asteroid.

00:10:45.967 --> 00:10:47.667
OK, I give you the
solar constant--

00:10:47.667 --> 00:10:52.033
that's how much radiation
is reaching that--

00:10:52.033 --> 00:10:53.333
and I give you its albedo.

00:10:53.333 --> 00:10:56.000
So what are you going to do?

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.433
Here's the thing here.

00:10:58.433 --> 00:11:01.667
So if you've got this little
asteroid, it's got a certain

00:11:01.667 --> 00:11:03.267
value of the solar constant.

00:11:03.267 --> 00:11:06.900
It's going to be different for
Earth, because it's closer to

00:11:06.900 --> 00:11:08.600
the Sun, so the solar constant's
going to be a

00:11:08.600 --> 00:11:11.567
little bit larger.

00:11:11.567 --> 00:11:13.033
Really, you've got
to make the same

00:11:13.033 --> 00:11:14.500
assumption we made in class.

00:11:14.500 --> 00:11:16.633
You're going to have to assume
that you've reached some kind

00:11:16.633 --> 00:11:19.900
of a steady-state temperature,
where it's receiving an amount

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:22.800
of radiation per unit of time
and emitting at the

00:11:22.800 --> 00:11:24.333
same rate to space.

00:11:24.333 --> 00:11:27.733
And then you've got to find the
temperature of the object

00:11:27.733 --> 00:11:30.833
that allows it to be in that
steady-state balance.

00:11:30.833 --> 00:11:35.267
If the temperature's too cold,
it won't be radiating enough

00:11:35.267 --> 00:11:36.333
to be in steady-state.

00:11:36.333 --> 00:11:40.200
If it's too hot, it'll be
radiating too much to be in

00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:40.867
steady state.

00:11:40.867 --> 00:11:43.033
So there's only one temperature
that'll allow it

00:11:43.033 --> 00:11:45.000
to balance its heat, and that's
the one that you can

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:47.000
derive from this formula.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:50.133
So solar constant, 1 minus the
albedo, over 4 times the

00:11:50.133 --> 00:11:51.233
Stefan-Boltzmann constant.

00:11:51.233 --> 00:11:55.967
So 2,000 watts per square meter,
1 minus the albedo, 4--

00:11:55.967 --> 00:11:57.733
there's the Stefan-Boltzmann
constant--

00:11:57.733 --> 00:12:02.633
take the fourth root, 257 K.

00:12:02.633 --> 00:12:03.900
Any questions on that?

00:12:07.067 --> 00:12:10.433
I think people did pretty
