00:12:10.433 --> 00:12:14.767
Question six, explain why a
planet like Earth will have

00:12:14.767 --> 00:12:18.600
lost its light gases over
geologic time but retained its

00:12:18.600 --> 00:12:19.333
heavier gases.

00:12:19.333 --> 00:12:24.667
So the point is the Earth is
in this middle category of

00:12:24.667 --> 00:12:28.533
planets where it's large enough
to retain the heavier

00:12:28.533 --> 00:12:33.500
gases but not large enough to
retain the light gases.

00:12:33.500 --> 00:12:36.733
And the way one reasons that
out is to realize that the

00:12:36.733 --> 00:12:39.733
Earth has a certain
escape velocity--

00:12:39.733 --> 00:12:42.967
that's the velocity needed
for particles to escape--

00:12:42.967 --> 00:12:45.400
and that is independent of
the particle itself.

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:48.500
That's just a fixed value.

00:12:48.500 --> 00:12:53.067
Then the light molecules
are moving rapidly.

00:12:53.067 --> 00:12:56.867
The heavier molecules are
moving more slowly.

00:12:56.867 --> 00:13:00.333
And it turns out that enough
of the light molecules are

00:13:00.333 --> 00:13:04.100
exceeding the escape velocity,
so we will have lost that over

00:13:04.100 --> 00:13:05.267
geologic time.

00:13:05.267 --> 00:13:09.667
But the heavier molecules are
moving slowly enough, so they

00:13:09.667 --> 00:13:13.267
do not exceed the escape
velocity, and they can be

00:13:13.267 --> 00:13:15.833
retained gravitationally
by the planet.

00:13:15.833 --> 00:13:20.033
So most of you got that, while a
few of you buggered up those

00:13:20.033 --> 00:13:21.367
descriptions a little bit.

