00:18:52.033 --> 00:18:54.000
Unstable lapse rate.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:58.833
An unstable lapse rate is an
atmospheric lapse rate--

00:18:58.833 --> 00:19:01.133
which, as you know, is the
rate at which temperature

00:19:01.133 --> 00:19:06.367
changes with height, that's a
definition of a lapse rate--

00:19:06.367 --> 00:19:11.733
that is more negative than
the adiabatic value.

00:19:11.733 --> 00:19:13.233
The dry adiabatic
value is minus

00:19:13.233 --> 00:19:14.833
9.8 degrees per kilometer.

00:19:14.833 --> 00:19:17.667
So if it's more negative than
that, that would mean, for

00:19:17.667 --> 00:19:24.033
example, minus 10, minus 11,
minus 12 degrees Celsius per

00:19:24.033 --> 00:19:26.467
kilometer would be an
unstable lapse rate.

00:19:26.467 --> 00:19:30.333
If it's less negative or
positive, like minus five

00:19:30.333 --> 00:19:33.800
degrees per kilometer, minus
two, minus one, zero, plus

00:19:33.800 --> 00:19:37.733
two, plus five, those would
all be stable lapse rates.

00:19:37.733 --> 00:19:40.500
And the characteristic of that
is that when a parcel rises,

00:19:40.500 --> 00:19:48.233
then, it cools less rapidly than
the environment in which

00:19:48.233 --> 00:19:50.200
it's penetrating.

00:19:50.200 --> 00:19:53.700
And therefore, it ends up
warmer than its new

00:19:53.700 --> 00:19:55.567
environment.

00:19:55.567 --> 00:19:58.633
And that'll allow it to continue
to rise, and it'll

00:19:58.633 --> 00:20:03.000
lead to convection if
you try to set up an

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:04.633
unstable lapse rate.

00:20:04.633 --> 00:20:08.033
Archimedes' Law, few
of you got this.

00:20:08.033 --> 00:20:15.067
I guess it's because it's not
in the book, and I only

00:20:15.067 --> 00:20:16.633
mentioned it once in class.

00:20:16.633 --> 00:20:19.567
But still I was a little bit
surprised, because I think

00:20:19.567 --> 00:20:20.500
it's well known.

00:20:20.500 --> 00:20:25.200
But the Archimedes' Law I'm
referring to here is that the

00:20:25.200 --> 00:20:31.767
buoyancy force that acts on an
object immersed in a fluid is

00:20:31.767 --> 00:20:36.533
equal to the weight of
the fluid displaced.

00:20:36.533 --> 00:20:39.433
So if I take a basketball and I
push it down into a swimming

00:20:39.433 --> 00:20:45.400
pool, I will feel a force trying
to push it back up

00:20:45.400 --> 00:20:50.967
that's equal to the weight of
the water that would be there

00:20:50.967 --> 00:20:53.867
if the ball were not.

00:20:53.867 --> 00:20:56.733
Now, that turns out to be pretty
simple to understand,

00:20:56.733 --> 00:21:01.300
because the pressure increases
as you go down in that pool,

00:21:01.300 --> 00:21:03.900
and therefore, the bottom of
the basketball feels higher

00:21:03.900 --> 00:21:05.133
pressure than the top.

00:21:07.600 --> 00:21:09.667
And that's what's causing
the buoyancy force.

00:21:09.667 --> 00:21:14.167
And the rate at which that
pressure increases as you go

00:21:14.167 --> 00:21:18.867
down is related to the density
of the surrounding fluid.

00:21:18.867 --> 00:21:21.300
That's why the surrounding fluid
comes in, because the

00:21:21.300 --> 00:21:24.033
surrounding fluid determines
the rate at which pressure

00:21:24.033 --> 00:21:25.233
increases with depth.

00:21:25.233 --> 00:21:28.300
And it's that increase that
gives you the buoyancy force

00:21:28.300 --> 00:21:30.800
pushing up on the ball.

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:36.033
So that's Archimedes' Law.

00:21:36.033 --> 00:21:38.267
The tropopause is the boundary
between the troposphere and

00:21:38.267 --> 00:21:39.567
the stratosphere.

00:21:39.567 --> 00:21:42.133
The troposphere is that first
layer where the temperature

00:21:42.133 --> 00:21:43.867
normally decreases
with height.

00:21:43.867 --> 00:21:47.333
The stratosphere is the next one
up where the temperature

00:21:47.333 --> 00:21:48.600
increases with height.

00:21:48.600 --> 00:21:54.500
Advection fog is fog caused by
moving warm air-- warm, moist

00:21:54.500 --> 00:21:56.733
air over a cold surface.

00:21:56.733 --> 00:21:59.400
Advection means horizontal
movement.

00:21:59.400 --> 00:22:02.133
So that's a clue.

00:22:02.133 --> 00:22:05.500
And if you take warm, moist air
and move it over a cold

00:22:05.500 --> 00:22:10.233
surface, it's going to lose
heat to that surface.

00:22:10.233 --> 00:22:12.500
As it cools down, the saturation
vapor pressure's

00:22:12.500 --> 00:22:13.567
going to drop.

00:22:13.567 --> 00:22:18.233
And the familiar story, you're
going to form some condensed

00:22:18.233 --> 00:22:21.633
water droplets in that way,
and that's the fog.

